3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of shingles involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ereactivation of latent virus from dorsal root ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E. After primary varicella-zoster virus infection (chickenpox), the virus establishes latency in sensory neurones. Years later, decreased immune function can allow viral reactivation, causing vesicular lesions in a dermatomal distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperinfection with a different viral strain\u003C/strong\u003E - Shingles represents reactivation of the original virus, not infection with a new strain\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect spread from active chickenpox lesions\u003C/strong\u003E - Shingles occurs independently of exposure to chickenpox cases\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune reaction to previous viral infection\u003C/strong\u003E - Shingles involves active viral replication, not an immune response to past infection\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary infection via respiratory droplets\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the transmission of chickenpox, not shingles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for reactivation include advanced age, immunosuppression, and stress. The characteristic unilateral, dermatomal distribution reflects viral spread along sensory nerve pathways from the affected dorsal root ganglion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Varicella-zoster virus establishes latency in dorsal root ganglia after primary infection (chickenpox).","Shingles occurs when latent varicella-zoster virus reactivates and travels along sensory nerves to cause vesicular lesions in a dermatomal distribution.","Shingles represents reactivation of the original infecting virus, not a new infection or immune response."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 355."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80275"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80275"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-08T18:03:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-08T18:05:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13655"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11717"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Viral infections","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-08T11:34:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-08T11:34:58+10:3